[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] Many types of machinery, engines, structures, and motors are load tested.
[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] The load may be at a designated safe working load (SWL), full load, or at an aggravated level of load.
[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] The governing contract, technical specification or test method contains the details of conducting the test.
[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] The purpose of a mechanical load test is to verify that all the component parts of a structure including materials, base-fixings are fit for task and loading it is designed for.
[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] The *Supply of Machinery (Safety) Regulation 1992 UK* state that load testing is undertaken before the equipment is put into service for the first time.
[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] Performance testing applies a safe working load (SWL), or other specified load, for a designated time in a governing test method, specification, or contract.
[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] Under the *Lifting Operations and Lifting Equipment Regulations 1998 UK* load testing after the initial test is required if a major component is replaced, if the item is moved from one location to another or as dictated by the competent person.
[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] The term *load testing* or stress testing is used in different ways in the professional software testing community.
[src:locust-load-testing/load-testing] *Load testing* generally refers to the practice of modeling the expected usage of a software program by simulating multiple users accessing the program concurrently.
[src:locust-load-testing/locust-io] A fundamental feature of Locust is that you describe all your test in Python code.
[src:locust-load-testing/locust-io] No need for clunky UIs or bloated XML, just plain code.
[src:locust-load-testing/locust-io] Read more detailed installations instructions in the documentation.
[src:locust-load-testing/locust-io] We are working on a hosted cloud version of Locust.
[src:locust-load-testing/locust-io] It's the simplest way to set up large-scale load tests with detailed reporting.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] In software quality assurance, **performance testing** is in general a testing practice performed to determine how a system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Performance testing, a subset of performance engineering, is a computer science practice which strives to build performance standards into the implementation, design and architecture of a system.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Tests examining the behavior under load are categorized into six basic types: Baseline test, load test, stress test, soak test, smoke test or isolation test.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Additionally to these basic types, configuration testing and Internet testing can be done.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Baseline testing is used to create a comparison point for other types of tests, e.g., for a stress test.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] By measuring how the system reacts in a "best case", for example only 5 parallel users, the other test types can be used to compare how the performance degrades in the worst case.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Load testing is the simplest form of performance testing.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] A load test is usually conducted to understand the behavior of the system under a specific expected load.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] This load can be the expected concurrent number of users on the application performing a specific number of transactions within the set duration.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] This test will give out the response times of all the important business critical transactions.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] The database, application server, etc. are also monitored during the test, this will assist in identifying bottlenecks in the application software and the hardware that the software is installed on.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Stress testing is normally used to understand the upper limits of capacity within the system.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] This kind of test is done to determine the system's robustness in terms of extreme load and helps application administrators to determine if the system will perform sufficiently if the current load goes well above the expected maximum.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Soak testing, also known as endurance testing or stability testing, is usually done to determine if the system can sustain the continuous expected load.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] During soak tests, memory utilization is monitored to detect potential leaks.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Also important, but often overlooked is performance degradation, i.e. to ensure that the throughput and/or response times after some long period of sustained activity are as good as or better than at the beginning of the test.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] It essentially involves applying a significant load to a system for an extended, significant period of time.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] The goal is to discover how the system behaves under sustained use.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Isolation testing is not unique to performance testing but involves repeating a test execution that resulted in a system problem.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Such testing can often isolate and confirm the fault domain.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Rather than testing for performance from a load perspective, tests are created to determine the effects of configuration changes to the system's components on the system's performance and behavior.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] A common example would be experimenting with different methods of load-balancing.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] This is a relatively new form of performance testing when global applications such as Facebook, Google and Wikipedia, are performance tested from load generators that are placed on the actual target continent whether physical machines or cloud VMs.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] These tests usually require an immense amount of preparation and monitoring to be executed successfully.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Many performance tests are undertaken without setting sufficiently realistic, goal-oriented performance goals.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] The first question from a business perspective should always be, "why are we performance-testing?".
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] These considerations are part of the business case of the testing.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] If a system identifies end-users by some form of log-in procedure then a concurrency goal is highly desirable.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] By definition this is the largest number of concurrent system users that the system is expected to support at any given moment.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] The work-flow of a scripted transaction may impact true concurrency especially if the iterative part contains the log-in and log-out activity.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] If the system has no concept of end-users, then performance goal is likely to be based on a maximum throughput or transaction rate.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] This refers to the time taken for one system node to respond to the request of another.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] A simple example would be a HTTP 'GET' request from browser client to web server.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] In terms of response time this is what all load testing tools actually measure.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] It may be relevant to set server response time goals between all nodes of the system.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Load-testing tools have difficulty measuring render-response time, since they generally have no concept of what happens within a node apart from recognizing a period of time where there is no activity 'on the wire'.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] To measure render response time, it is generally necessary to include functional test scripts as part of the performance test scenario.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Many load testing tools do not offer this feature.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] It is critical to detail performance specifications (requirements) and document them in any performance test plan.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Ideally, this is done during the requirements development phase of any system development project, prior to any design effort.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] See Performance Engineering for more details.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] The performance specification in terms of response time, concurrency, etc. is usually captured in a Service Level Agreement (SLA).
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Alternatively, the performance of a test case can be compared against its previous execution in order to identify regressions.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Since performance measurements are non-deterministic, capturing performance regressions requires appropriate repetition of the performance tests workload and appropriate statistical testing.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Additionally, performance testing is frequently used as part of the process of performance profile tuning.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] The idea is to identify the bottleneck – the part of the system which, if it is made to respond faster, will result in the overall system running faster.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Without such instrumentation one might have to have to rely on system monitoring.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Performance testing can be performed across the web, and even done in different parts of the country, since it is known that the response times of the internet itself vary regionally.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] It can also be done in-house, although routers would then need to be configured to introduce the lag that would typically occur on public networks.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Loads should be introduced to the system from realistic points.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] It is always helpful to have a statement of the likely peak number of users that might be expected to use the system at peak times.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] If there can also be a statement of what constitutes the maximum allowable 95 percentile response time, then an injector configuration could be used to test whether the proposed system met that specification.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] A stable build of the system which must resemble the production environment as closely as is possible.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] To ensure consistent results, the performance testing environment should be isolated from other environments, such as user acceptance testing (UAT) or development.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] As a best practice it is always advisable to have a separate performance testing environment resembling the production environment as much as possible.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] In performance testing, it is often crucial for the test conditions to be similar to the expected actual use.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] However, in practice this is hard to arrange and not wholly possible, since production systems are subjected to unpredictable workloads.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Test workloads may mimic occurrences in the production environment as far as possible, but only in the simplest systems can one exactly replicate this workload variability.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] Loosely-coupled architectural implementations (e.g.: SOA) have created additional complexities with performance testing.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] To truly replicate production-like states, enterprise services or assets that share a common infrastructure or platform require coordinated performance testing, with all consumers creating production-like transaction volumes and load on shared infrastructures or platforms.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] It is critical to the cost performance of a new system that performance test efforts begin at the inception of the development project and extend through to deployment.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] The later a performance defect is detected, the higher the cost of remediation.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] This is true in the case of functional testing, but even more so with performance testing, due to the end-to-end nature of its scope.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] It is crucial for a performance test team to be involved as early as possible, because it is time-consuming to acquire and prepare the testing environment and other key performance requisites.
[src:locust-load-testing/software-performance-testing] This part of performance testing mainly deals with creating/scripting the work flows of key identified business processes.
