[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] A system stress test refers to tests that put a greater emphasis on robustness, availability, and error handling under a heavy load, rather than on what would be considered correct behavior under normal circumstances.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] In particular, the goals of such tests may be to ensure the software does not crash in conditions of insufficient computational resources (such as memory or disk space), unusually high concurrency, or denial of service attacks.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] Achieving high branch coverage often involves writing *negative* test variations, that is, variations where the software is supposed to fail in some way, in addition to the usual *positive* test variations, which test intended usage.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] An example of a negative variation would be calling a function with illegal parameters.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] There is a limit to the branch coverage that can be achieved even with negative variations, however, as some branches may only be used for handling of errors that are beyond the control of the test.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] For example, a test would normally have no control over memory allocation, so branches that handle an "out of memory" error are difficult to test.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] Stress testing can achieve higher branch coverage by producing the conditions under which certain error handling branches are followed.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] The coverage can be further improved by using fault injection.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] Stress testing usually consists of testing beyond specified limits in order to determine failure points and test failure recovery.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] Load testing implies a controlled environment moving from low loads to high.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] Stress testing focuses on more random events, chaos and unpredictability.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] A Pattern-Based Software Testing Framework for Exploitability Evaluation of Metadata Corruption Vulnerabilities developed by Deng Fenglei, Wang Jian, Zhang Bin, Feng Chao, Jiang Zhiyuan, Su Yunfei discuss how there is increased attention in software quality assurance and protection.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] However, today's software still unfortunately fails to be protected from cyberattacks, especially in the presence of insecure organization of heap metadata.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] The authors aim to explore whether heap metadata could be corrupted and exploited by cyber-attackers, and they propose RELAY, a software testing framework to simulate human exploitation behavior for metadata corruption at the machine level.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] RELAY also makes use of the fewer resources consumed to solve a layout problem according to the exploit pattern, and generates the final exploit.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] A Methodology to Define Learning Objects Granularity developed by BENITTI, Fabiane Barreto Vavassori.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] The authors first discuss how learning object is one of the main research topics in the e-learning community in recent years and granularity is a key factor for learning object reuse.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] The authors then present a methodology to define the learning objects granularity in the computing area as well as a case study in software testing.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] Later, the authors carry out five experiments to evaluate the learning potential from the produced learning objects, as well as to demonstrate the possibility of learning object reuse.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] Results from the experiment are also presented in the article, which show that learning object promotes the understanding and application of the concepts.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] A recent article, Reliability Verification of Software Based on Cloud Service, have a ground breaking effect and it explores how software industry needs a way to measure reliability of each component of the software.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] In this article, a guarantee-verification method based on cloud service was proposed.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] The article first discusses how trustworthy each component's are will be defined in terms of component service guarantee-verification.
[src:locust-load-testing/stress-testing-software] Then an effective component model was defined in the article and based on the proposed model, the process of verifying a component service is illustrated in an application sample.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] A locust file is just a normal Python module, it can import code from other files or packages.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Here we define a class for the users that we will be simulating.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] It inherits from `HttpUser` which gives each user a `client` attribute, which is an instance of `HttpSession`, that can be used to make HTTP requests to the target system that we want to load test.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] When a test starts, locust will create an instance of this class for every user that it simulates, and each of these users will start running within their own green gevent thread.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For a file to be a valid locustfile it must contain at least one class inheriting from `User`.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Our class defines a `wait_time` that will make the simulated users wait between 1 and 5 seconds after each task (see below) is executed.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Methods decorated with `@task` are the core of your locust file.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For every running User, Locust creates a greenlet (a coroutine or “micro-thread”), that will call those methods.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Code within a task is executed sequentially (it is just regular Python code), so `/world` won’t be called until the response from `/hello` has been received.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] We’ve declared two tasks by decorating two methods with `@task`, one of which has been given a higher weight (3).
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] When our `QuickstartUser` runs it’ll pick one of the declared tasks - in this case either `hello_world` or `view_items` - and execute it.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Tasks are picked at random, but you can give them different weighting.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] The above configuration will make Locust three times more likely to pick `view_items` than `hello_world`.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] When a task has finished executing, the User will then sleep for its specified wait time (in this case between 1 and 5 seconds).
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Note that only methods decorated with `@task` will be picked, so you can define your own internal helper methods any way you like.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] The `self.client` attribute makes it possible to make HTTP calls that will be logged by Locust.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For information on how to make other kinds of requests, validate the response, etc, see Using the HTTP Client.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] HttpUser is not a real browser, and thus will not parse an HTML response to load resources or render the page.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] In the `view_items` task we load 10 different URLs by using a variable query parameter.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] In order to not get 10 separate entries in Locust’s statistics - since the stats is grouped on the URL - we use the name parameter to group all those requests under an entry named `"/item"` instead.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Additionally we’ve declared an *on_start* method.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] A method with this name will be called for each simulated user when they start.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For more info see on_start and on_stop methods.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] You can use har2locust to generate locustfiles based on a browser recording (HAR-file).
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] It is particularly useful for beginners that are not used to writing their own locustfile, but also highly customizable for more advanced use cases.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] It may not always generate correct locustfiles, and its interface may change between versions.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] A user class represents one type of user/scenario for your system.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] When you do a test run you specify the number of concurrent users you want to simulate and Locust will create an instance per user.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] A User’s `wait_time` method makes it easy to introduce delays after each task execution.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If no *wait_time* is specified, the next task will be executed as soon as one finishes.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For example, if you want Locust to run 500 task iterations per second at peak load, you could use *wait_time = constant_throughput(0.1)* and a user count of 5000.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Wait time can only constrain the throughput, not launch new Users to reach the target.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] So, in our example, the throughput will be less than 500 if the time for the task iteration exceeds 10 seconds.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Wait time is applied *after* task execution, so if you have a high spawn rate/ramp up you may end up exceeding your target during ramp-up.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Wait times apply to *tasks*, not requests.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For example, if you specify *wait_time = constant_throughput(2)* and do two requests in your tasks, your request rate/RPS will be 4 per User.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] It’s also possible to declare your own wait_time method directly on your class.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For example, the following User class would sleep for one second, then two, then three, etc.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If more than one user class exists in the file, and no user classes are specified on the command line, Locust will spawn an equal number of each of the user classes.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If you wish to simulate more users of a certain type than another you can set a weight attribute on those classes.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Also, you can set the `fixed_count` attribute.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] In this case, the weight attribute will be ignored and only that exact number users will be spawned.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] These users are spawned before any regular, weighted ones.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] In the example below, only one instance of AdminUser will be spawned, to make some specific work with more accurate control of request count independently of total user count.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] The host attribute is a URL prefix (e.g.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] `https://google.com`) to the host you want to test.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] It is automatically added to requests, so you can do `self.client.get("/")` for example.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] You can overwrite this value in Locust’s web UI or on the command line, using the `--host` option.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] A User class can have tasks declared as methods under it using the `@task` decorator, but one can also specify tasks using the *tasks* attribute, which is described in more details below.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] A reference to the `environment` in which the user is running.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Use this to interact with the environment, or the `runner` which it contains.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If run on a standalone locust instance, this will stop the entire run.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If run on worker node, it will stop that particular node.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Users (and TaskSets) can declare an `on_start` method and/or `on_stop` method.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] A User will call its `on_start` method when it starts running, and its `on_stop` method when it stops running.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For a TaskSet, the `on_start` method is called when a simulated user starts executing that TaskSet, and `on_stop` is called when the simulated user stops executing that TaskSet (when `interrupt()` is called, or the user is killed).
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] When a load test is started, an instance of a User class will be created for each simulated user and they will start running within their own greenlet.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] When these users run they pick tasks that they execute, sleep for awhile, and then pick a new task and so on.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] The easiest way to add a task for a User is by using the `task` decorator.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Another way to define the tasks of a User is by setting the `tasks` attribute.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] The *tasks* attribute is either a list of Tasks, or a *<Task : int>* dict, where Task is either a python callable or a TaskSet class.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If the task is a normal python function they receive a single argument which is the User instance that is executing the task.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If the tasks attribute is specified as a list, each time a task is to be performed, it will be randomly chosen from the *tasks* attribute.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If however, *tasks* is a dict - with callables as keys and ints as values - the task that is to be executed will be chosen at random but with the int as ratio.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] and then Python’s `random.choice()` is used to pick tasks from the list.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] By tagging tasks using the `@tag` decorator, you can be picky about what tasks are executed during the test using the `--tags` and `--exclude-tags` arguments.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If you started this test with `--tags tag1`, only *task1* and *task2* would be executed during the test.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If you started it with `--tags tag2 tag3`, only *task2* and *task3* would be executed.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] `--exclude-tags` will behave in the exact opposite way.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] So, if you start the test with `--exclude-tags tag3`, only *task1*, *task2*, and *task4* will be executed.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Exclusion always wins over inclusion, so if a task has a tag you’ve included and a tag you’ve excluded, it will not be executed.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If you want to run some setup code as part of your test, it is often enough to put it at the module level of your locustfile, but sometimes you need to do things at particular times in the run.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For this need, Locust provides event hooks.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If you need to run some code at the start or stop of a load test, you should use the `test_start` and `test_stop` events.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] The `init` event is triggered at the beginning of each Locust process.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] This is especially useful in distributed mode where each worker process (not each user) needs a chance to do some initialization.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] See extending locust using event hooks for other events and more examples of how to use them.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] `HttpUser` is the most commonly used `User`.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] It adds a `client` attribute which is used to make HTTP requests.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] `client` is an instance of `HttpSession`.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] HttpSession is a subclass/wrapper for `requests.Session`, so its features are well documented and should be familiar to many.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] What HttpSession adds is mainly reporting of the request results into Locust (success/fail, response time, response length, name).
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Just like `requests.Session`, it preserves cookies between requests so it can easily be used to log in to websites.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] HttpSession catches any `requests.RequestException` thrown by Session (caused by connection errors, timeouts or similar), instead returning a dummy Response object with *status_code* set to 0 and *content* set to None.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Requests are considered successful if the HTTP response code is OK (<400), but it is often useful to do some additional validation of the response.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] You can even avoid logging a request at all by throwing an exception and then catching it outside the with-block.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Or you can throw a locust exception, like in the example below, and let Locust catch it.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] It’s very common for websites to have pages whose URLs contain some kind of dynamic parameter(s).
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Often it makes sense to group these URLs together in User’s statistics.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] This can be done by passing a *name* argument to the `HttpSession's` different request methods.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] There may be situations where passing in a parameter into request function is not possible, such as when interacting with libraries/SDK’s that wrap a Requests session.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] An alternative way of grouping requests is provided by setting the `client.request_name` attribute.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If you want to chain multiple groupings with minimal boilerplate, you can use the `client.rename_request()` context manager.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Using catch_response and accessing request_meta directly, you can even rename requests based on something in the response.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] To improve performance, we configure requests to not look for HTTP proxy settings in the environment by setting requests.Session’s trust_env attribute to `False`.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If you don’t want this, you can manually set `locust_instance.client.trust_env` to `True`.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For further details, refer to the documentation of requests.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] By default, connections are reused by an HttpUser, even across tasks runs.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] Or you can close the entire requests.Session object (this also deletes cookies, closes the SSL session etc).
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] This has some CPU overhead (and the response time of the next request will be higher due to SSL renegotiation etc), so dont use this unless you really need it.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] As every `HttpUser` creates new `HttpSession`, every user instance has its own connection pool.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] This is similar to how real users (browsers) would interact with a web server.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] If you instead want to share connections, you can use a single pool manager.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] To do this, set `pool_manager` class attribute to an instance of `urllib3.PoolManager`.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For more configuration options, refer to the urllib3 documentation.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] TaskSets is a way to structure tests of hierarchical websites/systems.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] It’s important to remember that the locustfile.py is just an ordinary Python module that is imported by Locust.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] From this module you’re free to import other python code just as you normally would in any Python program.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] The current working directory is automatically added to python’s `sys.path`, so any python file/module/packages that resides in the working directory can be imported using the python `import` statement.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] For small tests, keeping all the test code in a single `locustfile.py` should work fine, but for larger test suites, you’ll probably want to split the code into multiple files and directories.
[src:locust-load-testing/writing-a-locustfile] How you structure the test source code is of course entirely up to you, but we recommend that you follow Python best practices.
